{{EM software tool |name=SPARX |website=http://sparx-em.org/sparxwiki |long description=SPARX (Single Particle Analysis for Resolution eXtension) is a new image processing environment with a particular emphasis on transmission electron microscopy (TEM) structure determination. It includes a user interface that provides a complete graphical programming environment with a novel data/process-flow infrastructure, an extensive library of python scripts that perform specific TEM-related computational tasks, and a core library of fundamental C++ image processing functions. In addition, SPARX relies on the EMAN2 library. |version=2.0 |contact=pawel.a.penczek@uth.tmc.edu |os support=Most platforms |image support=Most formats |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:BSD licenses|BSD]] |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Hohn M, Tang G, Goodyear G, ''et al.'' |title=SPARX, a new environment for Cryo-EM image processing |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=47–55 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=16931051 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.07.003 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Baldwin PR, Penczek PA |title=The Transform Class in SPARX and EMAN2 |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=250–61 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=16861004 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.06.002 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=SPIDER |website=http://www.wadsworth.org/spider_doc/spider/docs/spider.html |long description=SPIDER (System for Processing Image Data from Electron microscopy and Related fields) is an image processing system for electron microscopy. Contains numerous operations for: 3D reconstruction, averaging of single particle macromolecule specimens, multivariate statistical classification of images, and electron tomography. Computational modules are written in Fortran and the visualization GUI is written in C. Developed and maintained since 1978. |version=18.10+ |contact=spider@wadsworth.org |os support=Unix (Linux, Mac OS X) |image support=SPIDER, CCP4, Emispic, MRC, PDB, Raw |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:GNU General Public License|GPL]] |program language=Fortran, C |ref1={{cite journal |author=Frank J, Radermacher M, Penczek P, Zhu J, Li Y, Ladjadj M, Leith A |title=SPIDER and WEB: processing and visualization of images in 3D electron microscopy and related fields |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=116 |issue=1 |pages=190–9 |year=1996 |pmid=8742743 |doi=10.1006/jsbi.1996.0030 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Baxter WT, Leith A, Frank J |title=SPIRE: the SPIDER reconstruction engine |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=56–63 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=17055743 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.07.019 |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Yang C, Penczek PA, Leith A, ''et al.'' |title=The parallelization of SPIDER on distributed-memory computers using MPI |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=240–9 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=16859923 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.05.011 |url=}} |ref4={{cite journal |author=Shaikh TR, Gao H, Baxter WT, ''et al.'' |title=SPIDER image processing for single-particle reconstruction of biological macromolecules from electron micrographs |journal=Nat Protoc |volume=3 |issue=12 |pages=1941–74 |year=2008 |pmid=19180078 |pmc=2737740 |doi=10.1038/nprot.2008.156 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Suprim |website=http://ami.scripps.edu/redmine/projects/ami/wiki/Suprim |long description=A flexible, modular software package intended for the processing of electron microscopy images. The system consists of a set of image processing tools or filters,written in the C programming language, and a command line style user interface based on the UNIX shell. The pipe and filter structure of UNIX and the availability of command files in the form of shell scripts eases the construction of complex image processing procedures from the simpler tools. |version=5.5 |contact=amisoftware@scripps.edu |os support=Unix |image support=MRC/suprim |cost=Free/Open Source |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Schroeter JP, Bretaudiere JP |title=SUPRIM: easily modified image processing software |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=116 |issue=1 |pages=131–7 |year=1996 |pmid=8742734 |doi=10.1006/jsbi.1996.0021 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Xmipp |website=http://xmipp.cnb.csic.es/ |long description="X-Window-based Microscopy Image Processing Package", is a comprehensive package for single-particle analysis, which allows performing the entire 3D-EM image processing work-flow, from micrograph preprocessing to 3D model refinement. Among other tools, Xmipp contains programs for ART+blobs reconstruction, self-organizing maps and maximum-likelihood classification (in 2D and 3D). The software is written in C++ and designed in a highly modular way. Stand-alone programs may be invoked from the UNIX command line, or via standardized python scripts. A graphical user interface to the python scripts (written in python-tk) makes running Xmipp straightforward also for novice users. |version=3.1 |contact=xmipp@cnb.csic.es |os support=UNIX |image support=HDF5, SPIDER, MRC/CCP4, IMAGIC, PIF, Gatan DM3, TIFF, JPEG, EM, SPE |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:GNU General Public License|GPL]] |program language=C++, Python, Java |ref1={{cite journal |author=Sorzano CO, Marabini R, Velázquez-Muriel J, ''et al.'' |title=Xmipp 3.0: An improved software suite for image processing in electron microscopy |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=184 |issue=2 |pages=321–328 |year=2013 |month=November |pmid= |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2013.09.015 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Sorzano CO, Marabini R, Velázquez-Muriel J, ''et al.'' |title=XMIPP: a new generation of an open-source image processing package for electron microscopy |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=148 |issue=2 |pages=194–204 |year=2004 |month=November |pmid=15477099 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2004.06.006 |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Scheres SH, Núñez-Ramírez R, Sorzano CO, Carazo JM, Marabini R |title=Image processing for electron microscopy single-particle analysis using XMIPP |journal=Nat Protoc |volume=3 |issue=6 |pages=977–90 |year=2008 |pmid=18536645 |pmc=2778070 |doi=10.1038/nprot.2008.62 |url=}} }}
== Specific packages ==
Packages that offer a comprehensive set of tools to permit the analysis of data in a single class of structural problem. For example packages specifically focused on objects with helical, icosahedral, crystalline symmetry, etc.
=== Two-dimensional crystals ===
{{EM software tool |name=2dx |website=http://2dx.org/ |long description=A software system designed as a user friendly, platform-independent software package for electron crystallography. 2dx assists in the management of an image-processing project, guides the user through the processing of 2D crystal images, and provides transparence for processing tasks and results. Algorithms are implemented in the form of script templates reminiscent of c-shell scripts. It includes a single-particle Maximum Likelihood module, and 3D merging capability. 2dx builds upon the MRC programs, which were extended by additional functions to interface with the GUI of 2dx, and to implement the optionally automatic processing. |version=3.1.0 |contact=Henning.Stahlberg@unibas.ch |os support=Mac OS X, Linux |image support=MRC, TIFF, CCP4 |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:GNU General Public License|GPL]] |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Gipson B, Zeng X, Zhang ZY, Stahlberg H |title=2dx--user-friendly image processing for 2D crystals |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=64–72 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=17055742 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.07.020 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Zeng X, Stahlberg H, Grigorieff N |title=A maximum likelihood approach to two-dimensional crystals |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=160 |issue=3 |pages=362–74 |year=2007 |month=December |pmid=17964808 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2007.09.013 |url=}} }}
=== Icosahedral viruses ===
{{EM software tool |name=AUTO3DEM |website=http://cryoem.ucsd.edu/programs.shtm |long description=An automation system designed to accelerate the computationally intensive process of three-dimensional structure determination from images of vitrified icosahedral virus particles. With minimal user input and intervention, AUTO3DEM manages the flow of data between the major image reconstruction programs, monitors the progress of the computations, and intelligently updates the input parameters as the resolution of the model is improved. |version=2.02 |contact=sinkovit@sdsc.edu |os support=Linux, UNIX |image support=PIF |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:BSD licenses|BSD license]] |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Yan X, Sinkovits RS, Baker TS |title=AUTO3DEM--an automated and high throughput program for image reconstruction of icosahedral particles |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=73–82 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=17029842 |pmc=1847775 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.08.007 |url=}} }}
=== Helices ===
{{EM software tool |name=BBHP - Burnham-Brandeis Helical Package |website=http://coan.burnham.org/other-projects/ |long description=The Brandeis Helical Package has been in use in one form or another for quite some time. Originally developed for VAX/VMS it has been modified, expanded, and ported several times. We first ported the package to Linux in 2006, using the Portland Group compilers. Subsequently we rewrote portions of the fortran code which were not supported by GNU fortran (g77) and now the package compiles and runs with gcc/g77. This has allowed us to support extra modern platforms. The re-christened Burnham-Brandeis Helical Package will now run on 32-bit Linux, 64-bit Linux, Mac OS X (Intel) and even Windows running Cygwin. At the same time, when porting to Linux, we took the opportunity to replace the main GUI portions of the package with updated programs. We had spent some time modifying the Tcl/Tk-based GUI programs Tkir (image viewer) and Tkll (layerline viewer) from SUPRIM to support a plugin architecture, where we could write new plugins to add functionality without further modifications to the core code-base. The first, tkinterp, provides an interface in Tkir for selecting layerlines, replacing the old interp program. The second, brandeisll, is a Tkll plugin to provide support for displaying the Burnham-Brandeis Helical Package "interp" layerline and bessel-function format. We've also included as part of the package, the AVID software for analyzing the variance within the helix. |version=20.0 |contact=coan@burnham.org |os support=Linux |image support=MRC |cost=Free |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Owen CH, Morgan DG, DeRosier DJ |title=Image analysis of helical objects: the Brandeis Helical Package |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=116 |issue= |pages=167–175 |year=1996 |month= |pmid=8742740 |doi= |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Rost LE, Hanein D, DeRosier DJ |title=Reconstruction of symmetry deviations: a procedure to analyze partially decorated F-actin and other incomplete structures |journal=Ultramicroscopy |volume=72 |issue= |pages=187–197 |year=1998 |month= |pmid=9639941 |doi= |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=IHRSR |website= |long description=The iterative helical real space reconstruction (IHRSR) algorithm can recontruct helical filaments under conditions when traditional Fourier–Bessel approaches sometimes fail. For example when there is disorder or heterogeneity present, when the specimens diffract weakly, or when Bessel functions overlap. |version= |contact=egelman@virginia.edu |os support=Linux |image support=SPIDER |cost=Free |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Egelman EH |title=The iterative helical real space reconstruction method: surmounting the problems posed by real polymers |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=83–94 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=16919474 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.05.015 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Phoelix |website=http://ami.scripps.edu/redmine/projects/ami/wiki/Phoelix |long description=A set of procedures and algorithms for helical processing that we refer to as the PHOELIX package. The package was developed to provide a time-efficient and semiautomated method for determining a three-dimensional density map from a specimen with helical symmetry. The procedures which are part of PHOELIXn are drawn from the original MRC helical processing suite with extensions principally developed using the SUPRIM image processing package. The package in its current form has been optimized for the processing of actomyosin filaments but has been modified and applied to other helical structures. |version=1.3 |contact=amisoftware@scripps.edu |os support=Unix |image support=MRC/suprim |cost=Free/Open Source |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Whittaker M, Carragher BO, Milligan RA |title=PHOELIX: a package for semi-automated helical reconstruction |journal=Ultramicroscopy |volume=58 |issue=3-4 |pages=245–59 |year=1995 |month=June |pmid=7571117 |doi= |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Carragher B, Whittaker M, Milligan RA |title=Helical processing using PHOELIX |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=116 |issue=1 |pages=107–12 |year=1996 |pmid=8742731 |doi=10.1006/jsbi.1996.0018 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Ruby-Helix |website=http://structure.m.u-tokyo.ac.jp/English/software/Ruby-Helix-Page/ruby-helix.html |long description=Set of programs for the analysis of “helical” objects with or without a seam. Ruby-Helix is built on top of the Ruby programming language and is the first implementation of asymmetric helical reconstruction for practical image analysis. It also allows easier and semi-automated analysis, performing iterative unbending and accurate determination of the repeat length. |version=1.0 |contact=mkikkawa@m.u-tokyo.ac.jp |os support=Fedora, Mac OS X |image support=MRC |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:GNU General Public License|GPL]] |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Metlagel Z, Kikkawa YS, Kikkawa M |title=Ruby-Helix: an implementation of helical image processing based on object-oriented scripting language |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=95–105 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=16996276 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.07.015 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Kikkawa M |title=A new theory and algorithm for reconstructing helical structures with a seam |journal=J. Mol. Biol. |volume=343 |issue=4 |pages=943–55 |year=2004 |month=October |pmid=15476812 |doi=10.1016/j.jmb.2004.08.051 |url=}} }}
