{{EM software tool |name=TxBR |website=https://confluence.crbs.ucsd.edu/display/ncmir/TxBR |long description=Tomographic reconstruction from large-format electron microscope data requires special procedures to handle geometric distortions arising from electron optics as opposed to light-ray optics. In particular, electrons travel in curvilinear paths through the sample, and defocus and other aberrations can have significant effects. TxBR handles geometric nonlinearities associated with charged-particle optics, distortion due to sample warping, and transform sets associated with non-standard modes of data collection. In addition, TxBR makes provision for marker-free alignment and specialized montaging for tomography of serial sections. |version=3.0 |contact=sph at ncmir dot ucsd dot edu |os support=Linux, Windows (&ge; XP), Mac OS X (PowerPC and Intel) |image support=MRC |cost=Free |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite book |author=S. Phan, A. Lawrence |title=Congress on Image and Signal Processing, Vol. 2 |publisher= |year=2008 |pages=176-182 |chapter=Tomography of Large Format Electron Microscope Tilt Series: Image Alignment and Volume Reconstruction |isbn=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Lawrence A, Bouwer JC, Perkins G, Ellisman MH |title=Transform-based backprojection for volume reconstruction of large format electron microscope tilt series |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=154 |issue=2 |pages=144–67 |year=2006 |month=May |pmid=16542854 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2005.12.012 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=UCSF Tomography |website=http://www.msg.ucsf.edu/em/EMNEW2/tomography_page.html |long description=UCSF Tomography is an integrated software suite that provides full automation from target finding, sequential tomographic data collection, to real-time reconstruction for both single and dual axes as well as automated acquisition of random conical data sets. This software was implemented based upon a novel approach in which the compustage tilting is modeled as geometric rotation. The spatial movement of the sample as a result of stage tilting can be predicted based upon previously collected tomographic images. Therefore, there is no need to collect tracking and focusing images during the entire tomographic data collection. A significant dose saving can thus be achieved and is critical in collecting cryo tilt series. Real-time reconstruction is achieved by calculating a weighted back-projection on a small Linux cluster (five dual-processor computer nodes) concurrently with the UCSF tomography data collection running on the microscope’s computer, and using the fiducial-marker free alignment data generated during the data collection process. The real-time reconstructed 3D volume provides users with immediate feedback to fully asses all aspects of the experiment ranging from sample choice, ice thickness, experimental parameters to the quality of specimen preparation. To facilitate dual-axis tomographic data collection, a hierarchical scheme for target finding and relocation after specimen rotation was developed and integrated with the predictive data collection and real-time reconstruction, allowing full automation from target finding to data collection and to reconstruction of 3D volumes with little user intervention. An on-site scheme was developed for random conical data collection where tracking and focusing are performed at the same location as the final conical tilt images. Lower magnifications combined with short exposure are used to substantially reduce dose and to allow larger tilt steps. The system also includes a feature for montaging untilted images to ensure that all of the particles in the tilted image may be used in the reconstruction. |version=v7.7.4E4 |contact=agard@msg.ucsf.edu |os support=Windows 2000, XP |image support=MRC |cost=Free for academic use |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Zheng SQ, Keszthelyi B, Branlund E, ''et al.'' |title=UCSF tomography: an integrated software suite for real-time electron microscopic tomographic data collection, alignment, and reconstruction |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=138–47 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=16904341 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.06.005 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Zheng QS, Braunfeld MB, Sedat JW, Agard DA |title=An improved strategy for automated electron microscopic tomography |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=147 |issue=2 |pages=91–101 |year=2004 |month=August |pmid=15193638 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2004.02.005 |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Zheng SQ, Kollman JM, Braunfeld MB, Sedat JW, Agard DA |title=Automated acquisition of electron microscopic random conical tilt sets |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=157 |issue=1 |pages=148–55 |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=17169745 |pmc=2556511 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.10.026 |url=}} |ref4={{cite journal |author=Zheng SQ, Matsuda A, Braunfeld MB, Sedat JW, Agard DA |title=Dual-axis target mapping and automated sequential acquisition of dual-axis EM tomographic data |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=168 |issue=2 |pages=323–31 |year=2009 |month=November |pmid=19545637 |pmc=2776717 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2009.06.010 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=FEI Xplore3D™ Tomography Suite |website=http://www.fei.com/LifeSciences/ |long description=Xplore3D provides a complete solution for 3D tomographic acquisition, reconstruction, and visualization into one integrated package. The advanced capabilities include batch acquisition, dual-axis tomography, low-dose imaging, STEM tomography, energy filtering, and hardware acceleration for reconstruction. Batch scheduling permits unattended overnight data acquisition from multiple grid positions. Accurate, interactive alignment routines can use cross-correlation (no markers needed), bead tracking, or general feature tracking. Advanced reconstruction techniques include weighted back-projection, ART, and SIRT. Xplore3D includes a post-alignment and reconstruction module, Inspect3D. |contact=robert dot snyder at fei dot com |os support=Windows XP, |image support=most image formats |cost=Price available upon request |license=Perpetual right-to-use license |ref1={{cite journal |author=R.H.M. Schoenmakers, R.A. Perquin, T.F. Fliervoet, W. Voorhout, H. Schirmacher |title=New software for high resolution, high throughput electron tomography |journal=Microscopy and Analysis |volume=19 |issue=4 |pages=5-6 |year=2005 |month=July}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Li Peng, Sergey Ryazantsev, Ren Sun, Z. Hong Zhou |title=Three-Dimensional Visualization of Gammaherpesvirus Life Cycle in Host Cells by Electron Tomography |journal=Structure |volume=18 |issue=1 |pages=47-58 |year=2010 |month=January |pmid=20152152 |doi=10.1016/j.str.2009.10.017 |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Linda F. van Driel, Jack A. Valentijn, Karine M. Valentijn, Roman I. Koning, Abraham J. Koster |title=Tools for correlative cryo-fluorescence microscopy and cryo-electron tomography applied to whole mitochondria in human endothelial cells |journal=European Journal of Cell Biology |volume=88 |issue=11 |pages=669-684 |year=2009 |month=November |pmid=19726102 |doi=10.1016/j.ejcb.2009.07.002 |url=}} 