== Application tools ==
=== Subvolume averaging ===
{{EM software tool |name=Dynamo |website=http://www.dynamo-em.org |long description=Dynamo is a software package for subtomogram averaging of Cryo-EM data. It is intended to provide users with big flexibility when adding new algorithms into standard procedures and adapting them for different computing environments as desktops, multicore machines, (multi)GPUs or clusters of CPUs. |version=1.0.116 |contact=daniel.castano@unibas.ch |os support=Linux, Mac OS, Windows |image support= .em, .spi, .mrc |cost=Free for academic use |license= GPL / BSD |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author= Castaño-Díez D, Kudryashev M, Arheit M, Stahlberg H|title= Dynamo: A flexible, user-friendly development tool for subtomogram averaging of cryo-EM data in high-performance computing environments. |journal=J Struct Biology |volume=|issue=3|pages= |year=2012 |pmid= |doi= http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.jsb.2011.12.017|url= |postscript=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Jsubtomo |website=http://www.opic.ox.ac.uk/jsubtomo |long description=Jsubtomo is an open source software package based on Bsoft for averaging of tomographic sub-volumes. It includes tools for locating sub-volumes in tomograms using constrained cross-correlation, missing wedge-weighted averaging and refinement. Initial estimate of particle orientation can be easily included to constrain refinement. Python scripts are available for parallel processing and iterative refinement. |version=1.2 |contact=juha at strubi dot ox dot ac dot uk |os support=Linux, Mac OS, Windows |image support= Most, including .map, .mrc, .em, .spi, .img, .pif |cost=Free |license= |program language=C |ref1={{cite journal |author= Huiskonen JT, Hepojoki J, Laurinmäki P, Vaheri A, Lankinen H, Butcher SJ, Grünewald K.|title= Electron cryotomography of Tula hantavirus suggests a unique assembly paradigm for enveloped viruses.|journal= J Virology |volume=84|issue=10|pages=4889-97|year=2010|pmid= |doi= 10.1128/JVI.00057-10|url= |postscript=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=PEET |website=http://bio3d.colorado.edu/PEET |long description=PEET is an open-source package for subvolume alignment, averaging, and classification. PEET is most easily used in conjunction with IMOD. |version=1.8.0 |contact=john.heumann@colorado.edu |os support=Linux, Mac OS-X, Windows |image support= .mrc |cost=Free |license= GPL |program language=Matlab, C, C++ |ref1={{cite journal |author= Nicastro D, Schwartz C, Pierson J, Gaudette R, Porter M, McIntosh J.R. |title= The molecular architecture of axonemes revealed by cryoelectron tomography. |journal=Science |volume=313|issue=5789|pages=944-948 |year=2006 |pmid= |doi= 10.1126/science.1128618 |url= |postscript=}} }}
=== Mass measurements ===
{{EM software tool |name=MASDET |website=http://campus.uni-muenster.de/masdet.html |long description=A fast and user-friendly multiplatform software for mass determination by dark-field electron microscopy. MASDET offers several subroutines for the main mass analysis steps, namely image display and selection of regions of interest (ROI), mass evaluation and data analysis. Two program-modes constitute the core procedures for mass determination: (i) the program-mode AREA determines the mass-per-area of sheet-like structures (e.g., protein S-layers, thin organic and inorganic films) and the mass-per-box for globular structures (e.g., single macromolecules, globular assemblies, organic/inorganic nanoparticles), and (ii) the program-mode FILAMENT determines the mass-per-length for filamentous structures (e.g., intermediate filaments, DNA-protein complexes, tobacco mosaic virus, nanowires) in individual ROIs. The statistical analysis of the mass data in individual ROIs contains graphical data display (histograms and XY-plots) and allows up to 10 Gaussian curves to be fitted. The dark-field micrographs can also be recalculated to a mass-thickness profile and/or mass-thickness map using data from Monte Carlo simulations. |version=1.13 |contact=krzyzane at uni-muenster dot de |os support=Windows (both standalone program and p-files run from MATLAB); Mac OS X, Linux (p-files to be run from MATLAB) |image support=Basel IMAG, Muenster TIFF (other formats will be implemented by us on request) |cost=Free for academic use |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Krzyzanek V, Müller SA, Engel A, Reichelt R |title=MASDET--A fast and user-friendly multiplatform software for mass determination by dark-field electron microscopy |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=165 |issue=2 |pages=78–87 |year=2009 |month=February |pmid=19041401 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2008.10.006 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Krzyzanek V, Reichelt R |title=MONCA: A New MATLAB Package for Monte Carlo Simulation of Electron Scattering in Thin Specimens in the Energy Range 10 - 200 keV |journal=Microsc. Microanal. |volume=9 |issue=Suppl. 3 |pages=110-111 |year=2003 |month= |pmid= |doi=10.1017/S1431927603014065 |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?aid=173725}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Reichelt R, Engel A |title=Monte Carlo calculations of elastic and inelastic electron scattering in biological and plastic materials |journal=Ultramicrosc. |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=279-293 |year=1984 |month= |pmid= |doi=10.1016/0304-3991(84)90206-7 |url=}} }}
=== Data Acquisition ===
Packages that offer a tool or a set of tools to permit the analysis of data in one or more class of structural problems. These have generally been developed to manage one specific step in the structural analysis, for example CTF correction, particle picking etc.
{{EM software tool |name=Leginon |website=http://leginon.scripps.edu |long description=Leginon is a system designed for automated collection of images from a transmission electron microscope. Instruments supported: FEI Tecnai series TEM, Tietz and Gatan CCD cameras. On August 1, 2007, Leginon 1.4 was released as open source. |version=2.0 |contact=amisoftware@scripps.edu |os support=Linux/Windows |image support=MRC |cost=Free/Open source |license=[[w:Apache License|Apache 2.0]] |ref1={{cite journal |author=Suloway C, Pulokas J, Fellmann D, ''et al.'' |title=Automated molecular microscopy: the new Leginon system |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=151 |issue=1 |pages=41–60 |year=2005 |month=July |pmid=15890530 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2005.03.010 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Suloway C, Shi J, Cheng A, ''et al.'' |title=Fully automated, sequential tilt-series acquisition with Leginon |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=167 |issue=1 |pages=11–8 |year=2009 |month=July |pmid=19361558 |pmc=2724967 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2009.03.019 |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Stagg SM, Lander GC, Pulokas J, ''et al.'' |title=Automated cryoEM data acquisition and analysis of 284742 particles of GroEL |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=155 |issue=3 |pages=470–81 |year=2006 |month=September |pmid=16762565 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2006.04.005 |url=}} |ref4={{cite journal |author=Yoshioka C, Pulokas J, Fellmann D, Potter CS, Milligan RA, Carragher B |title=Automation of random conical tilt and orthogonal tilt data collection using feature-based correlation |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=159 |issue=3 |pages=335–46 |year=2007 |month=September |pmid=17524663 |pmc=2043090 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2007.03.005 |url=}} |ref5={{cite journal |author=Cheng A, Leung A, Fellmann D, ''et al.'' |title=Towards automated screening of two-dimensional crystals |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=160 |issue=3 |pages=324–31 |year=2007 |month=December |pmid=17977016 |pmc=2141647 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2007.09.012 |url=}} }}
=== Particle Selection ===
{{EM software tool |name=DoG Picker |website=http://ami.scripps.edu/redmine/projects/ami/wiki/DogPicker |long description=DoG Picker is a simple particle picker that picks particles that resemble a blob using the [[w:Difference of Gaussians|Difference of Gaussians]] algorithm. It is intergrated into the TiltPicker program (below), |version=0.2 |contact=appion@scripps.edu |os support=Unix |image support=MRC |cost=Free/Open source |license=[[w:Apache License|Apache License v2.0]] |program language=Python |ref1={{cite journal |author=Voss NR, Yoshioka CK, Radermacher M, Potter CS, Carragher B |title=DoG Picker and TiltPicker: software tools to facilitate particle selection in single particle electron microscopy |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=166 |issue=2 |pages=205–13 |year=2009 |month=May |pmid=19374019 |pmc=2768396 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2009.01.004 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=FindEM |website=http://ami.scripps.edu/redmine/projects/ami/wiki/FindEM |long description=The FindEM program is based on projection matching using local real-space correlation with a series of templates. Real-space algorithms are traditionally relatively slow, but a fast Fourier based implementation of the real-space local correlation function has been introduced which is approximately two orders of magnitude faster for the projection matching application. This algorithm is referred to as the “Fast Local Correlation Function” or FLCF. |version=2.0 |contact=appion@scripps.edu |os support=Unix |image support=MRC |cost=Free/Open source |ref1={{Cite journal|first1=A.M.|last1=Roseman| year=2004|title=FindEM—a fast, efficient program for automatic selection of particles from electron micrographs | journal=Journal of Structural Biology|volume=145|issue=1-2|pages=91-99|doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2003.11.007|pmid=15065677}} |ref2={{Cite journal|first1=A.M.|last1=Roseman| year=2003|title=Particle finding in electron micrographs using a fast local correlation algorithm. | journal=Ultramicroscopy|volume=94|pages=225–236|issue=3-4|pmid=12524193}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Signature |website=http://emlab.rose2.brandeis.edu |long description=A particle selection system for molecular electron microscopy. It applies a hierarchical screening procedure to identify molecular particles in EM micrographs. The user interface of the program provides versatile functions to facilitate image data visualization, particle annotation and particle quality inspection. The system design emphasizes both functionality and usability. |version= |contact=niko @brandeis.edu |os support=Linux, Mac OS X, MS Windows |image support=MRC, TIFF |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:GNU General Public License|GPL]] |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=J. Z. |last1=Chen |coauthors=Grigorieff, N. |year=2007 |title=SIGNATURE: A single-particle selection system for molecular electron microscopy |journal=Journal of Structural Biology |volume=157 |issue= |pages=168-173 |pmid= |doi= |pmcid= }} }}
{{EM software tool |name=SwarmPS |website=http://www.imb.uq.edu.au/swarmps |long description=A specialised graphical user interface designed to streamline the process of particle selection from electron micrograph data sets. It provides implementations of both template matching and edge detection algorithms, has an intuitive and easy to use interface, and can be used to obtain useful results on most data sets that are generated in electron microscopy. Currently users can expect to select about 1000-4000 particles per hour of interaction. |version=0.9.2 |contact=d.woolford @imb.uq.edu.au |os support=Linux |image support=Most image formats |cost=Free for academic use under a software license agreement |license= |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=D. |last1=Woolford |coauthors=Ericksson, G., Rothnagel, R., Muller, D., Landsberg, M. J., Pantelic, R. S., McDowall, A., Pailthorpe, B., Young, P. R., Hankamer, B., and Banks, J. |year=2007 |title=SwarmPS: Rapid, semi-automated single particle selection software |journal=Journal of Structural Biology |volume=157 |issue= |pages=174-188 |pmid= |doi= |pmcid= }} }}
{{EM software tool |name=TiltPicker |website=http://ami.scripps.edu/redmine/projects/ami/wiki/TiltPicker |long description=A graphical user interface for picking particles from image tilt pairs for such applications as random conical tilt (RCT) and orthogonal tilt reconstruction (OTR). TiltPicker borrows its interface from Leginon and re-implements many of the tilt picking features of SPIDER WEB that can be run on modern computers. |version=2.0 |contact=vossman77@yahoo.com |os support=Linux, Mac OS X, Windows, other Unices |image support= |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:Apache License|Apache v2.0]] |ref1={{cite journal |author=Voss NR, Yoshioka CK, Radermacher M, Potter CS, Carragher B |title=DoG Picker and TiltPicker: software tools to facilitate particle selection in single particle electron microscopy |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=166 |issue=2 |pages=205–13 |year=2009 |month=May |pmid=19374019 |pmc=2768396 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2009.01.004 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=TMaCS |website=https://sites.google.com/site/rubinsteingroup/particle-selection |long description=Template Matching and Classification System. Template matching identifies candidate particle images while a Support Vector Machine algorithm is interactively trained to distinguish particles from non-particles. |version=1.0 |contact=john.rubinstein@utoronto.ca, jianhua.zhao@utoronto.ca |os support=Linux |image support=MRC |cost=Free/Open Source |license= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Zhao J, Brubaker MA, Rubinstein JL |title=TMaCS: A hybrid template matching and classification system for automated particle selection |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume=In Press |issue= |pages= |year=2013 |month= |pmid= |pmc= |doi= |url=}} }} }}
