{{EM software tool |name=iMODFIT |website=http://chaconlab.org/imodfit/index.html |long description=iMODFIT is an efficient tool for fast flexible fitting of atomic structures into low/medium resolution EM maps based on Normal Mode Analysis in internal Coordinates. It is able to deal with protein and nucleic acid structures with small ligands at several coarse-graining levels. Please, download the program and test by yourself the efficiency and robustness reached with this new approach. |version=1.02 |contact=pablo@chaconlab.org |os support=Linux |image support=CCP4, SITUS |cost=Free |license= |program language=C/C++ |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=J.R. |last1=López-Blanco |coauthors=Garzón, J.I. ; Chacón, P. |year=2011 |title=(in preparation) |journal= |volume= |issue= |pages= |pmid= |doi= |pmcid= }} }}
{{EM software tool |name=NORMA |website=http://www.elnemo.org/NORMA |long description=NORMA is a freely available software suite that allows the modelling of large conformational changes of high-resolution three-dimensional protein structures under the constraint of a low-resolution electron-density map. Typical applications are the interpretation of electron-microscopy data using atomic scale X-ray structural models. The software package provided should enable the interested user to perform flexible fitting on new cases without encountering major technical difficulties. The NORMA software suite includes three fully executable reference cases and extensive user instructions. It is comes with a Linux version of the URO fitting package (by J. Navaza) and the elNemo elastic network model normal mode analysis code (by Y.H. Sanejouand). |version=1.0 |contact=Karsten Suhre |os support=Linux |image support=EZD, CCP4, MRC, PIF |cost=Free |license= |program language= |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=K. |last1=Suhre |coauthors=Navaza, J., and Sanejouand, Y.H. |year=2006 |title=NORMA: a tool for flexible fitting of high resolution protein structures into low resolution electron microscopy derived density maps |journal=Acta Cryst |volume=D62 |issue= |pages=1098-1100 |pmid= |doi= |pmcid= }} }}
{{EM software tool |name=OpenStructure |website=http://www.openstructure.org |long description=OpenStructure is a software development platform tailored to the implementation of novel computational structural biology and molecular modeling methods. OpenStructure has been designed to handle and manipulate a wide range of data types as required in the field of integrative modeling, where data originating from a variety of experimental techniques are used to guide the model building process. The toolkit allows the development of sophisticated stand-alone applications, but also offers interfaces to flexibly incorporate external software, where appropriate, without the need to re-implement existing functionalities. At the top level, OpenStructure features a graphical user interface with components for rendering of biological macromolecules, density maps, image stacks, widgets for sequence analysis and graphical scene setup, and an integrated Python shell. While the graphical interface is conveniently used without prior knowledge of the underlying layers, the GUI maintains a tight integration with the scripting functionality. Any object that is visualized on the screen can be accessed at the Python level. Likewise, it is possible to create and manipulate graphical objects from within a script. This setup allows the combination of human-based and automatic data analysis, and freely customizing the graphical interface itself. |version=1.0.0 |contact=Torsten Schwede |os support=Win/Linux/MacOS X |image support=CCP4, DAT, TIFF, MRC, SPIDER, Nanoscope, PNG, SITUS, JPK, PDB, SDF, CRD, CHARMM trajectory files, maestro, many sequence and alignment formats |cost=Free |license=[[w:GNU Lesser General Public License|LGPL]] |program language=[[w:C++|C++]]/[[w:Python_(programming_language)|Python]] |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=M. |last1=Biasini |coauthors=Mariani V., Haas J., Scheuber S., Schenk A.D., Schwede T., and Philippsen A. |year=2010 |title=OpenStructure: a flexible software framework for computational structural biology |journal=Bioinformatics |volume=26 |issue=20 |pages=2626–2628 |pmid=20733063 |doi=10.1093/bioinformatics/btq481 |pmcid=PMC2951092 }} }}
{{EM software tool |name=PyMOL |website=http://pymol.org |long description= |version=1.2 |contact=licensing@schrodinger.com |os support=Linux, Unix, Mac OS X, and Windows |image support=CCP4, MRC, PDB, many more |cost=Subscription/Open Source |license= |program language=Python |ref1=''Unpublished'' }}
{{EM software tool |name=RIVEM |website=http://bilbo.bio.purdue.edu/~viruswww/Rossmann_home/softwares/river_programs/rivem.php |long description=Program developed to project electron density of virus radially onto a sphere that is then presented as a stereographic diagram. Features that constitute the viral surface can be simultaneously represented in terms of atoms, amino acid residues, potential charge distribution, and surface topology |version=3.2 |contact=xc@purdue.edu |os support=Linux, AIX |image support=XPLOR ASCII |cost=Free |license= |program language= |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=C. |last1=Xiao |coauthors=Rossmann, M. G. |year=2007 |title=Interpretation of electron density with stereographic roadmap projections |journal=Journal of Structural Biology |volume=158 |issue= |pages=182-187 |pmid= |doi= |pmcid= }} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Sculptor |website=http://sculptor.biomachina.org/ |long description=Sculptor is an interactive multi-resolution docking and visualization program for low-resolution density maps and atomic structures. We are developing Sculptor as a GUI-based extension of the Situs docking programs, to allow an interactive exploration and analysis of volumetric maps. Sculptor combines 3D rendering with advanced mathematical concepts like clustering techniques and pattern matching algorithms to permit an almost instantaneous fitting of the high-resolution structures and to facilitate typical post-processing work like map editing or resolution adjustment. |version=2.1 |contact=sculptor@biomachina.org |os support=Windows, Macintosh, Linux |image support=MRC, CCP4, SITUS, SPIDER |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:GNU Lesser General Public License|LGPL]] |program language=C++ |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=S. |last1=Birmanns |coauthors=Rusu M, Wriggers W |year=2011 |title=Using Sculptor and Situs for Simultaneous Assembly of Atomic Components into Low-Resolution Shapes |journal=J. Struct. Biol. |volume= |issue= |pages= |pmid= |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2010.11.002 |pmcid= }}
|ref2={{cite journal |author=Heyd J, Birmanns S|title=Immersive Structural Biology: A New Approach to Hybrid Modeling of Macromolecular Assemblies |journal=Virtual Reality |volume=13 |issue= |pages=245-255 |year=2009 |month=July |pmid= |pmc= |doi= |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Rusu M, Birmanns S, Wriggers W |title=Biomolecular pleiomorphism probed by spatial interpolation of coarse models |journal=Bioinformatics |volume=24 |issue=21 |pages=2460–6 |year=2008 |month=November |pmid=18757874 |pmc=2732278 |doi=10.1093/bioinformatics/btn461 |url=}} |ref4={{cite journal |author=Birmanns S, Wriggers W|title=Interactive Fitting Augmented by Force-Feedback and Virtual Reality |journal=J Struct Biol |volume=144 |issue= |pages=123-131 |year=2003 |month= |pmid= |pmc= |doi= |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=Situs |website=http://situs.biomachina.org/ |long description=Situs is a modular software package for the integration of biophysical data across the spatial resolution scales. It has been developed over the last decade with a focus on bridging the resolution gap between atomic structures, coarse-grained models, and volumetric data from low-resolution biophysical origins, such as electron microscopy, tomography, or small-angle scattering. Structural models can be created and refined with various flexible and rigid body docking strategies. The software consists of multiple, stand-alone programs for the format conversion, analysis, visualization, manipulation, and assembly of 3D data sets. |version=2.7 |contact=situs@biomachina.org |os support=Windows, Macintosh, Linux |image support=MRC, CCP4, SITUS, SPIDER, XPLOR, ASCII |cost=Free/Open Source |license=[[w:GNU General Public License|GPL]] |program language=C/C++ |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=W. |last1=Wriggers |coauthors= |year=2010 |title=Using Situs for the Integration of Multi-Resolution Structures |journal=Biophysical Reviews |volume=2 |issue= |pages=21-27 |pmid=20174447 |doi=10.1007/s12551-009-0026-3 |pmcid=PMC2821521 }} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Wriggers W, Chacón P |title=Modeling tricks and fitting techniques for multiresolution structures |journal=Structure |volume=9 |issue=9 |pages=779–88 |year=2001 |month=September |pmid=11566128 |doi= |url=}} |ref3={{cite journal |author=Chacón P, Wriggers W |title=Multi-resolution contour-based fitting of macromolecular structures |journal=J. Mol. Biol. |volume=317 |issue=3 |pages=375–84 |year=2002 |month=March |pmid=11922671 |doi=10.1006/jmbi.2002.5438 |url=}} |ref4={{cite journal |author=Rusu M, Birmanns S, Wriggers W |title=Biomolecular pleiomorphism probed by spatial interpolation of coarse models |journal=Bioinformatics |volume=24 |issue=21 |pages=2460–6 |year=2008 |month=November |pmid=18757874 |pmc=2732278 |doi=10.1093/bioinformatics/btn461 |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=UROX |website=http://sites.google.com/site/xsiebert/urox |long description=An interactive tool for fitting atomic models into electron microscopy reconstructions (or into envelopes derived from small-angle X-ray or neutron scattering). The correlation between the electron density of the atomic models and the map is calculated and updated as a model is moved on the graphical display with the help of the mouse. Calculations are performed in reciprocal-space and the symmetry of the reconstruction is taken into account. The computations are fast and an entire EM reconstruction can be used. Versions above 2.0 include Normal-Modes flexible fitting and "map on map" fitting (in addition to "model in map" fitting). |version=2.0.2 |contact=xsiebert@gmail.com |os support=Linux |image support=EZD, CCP4, MRC, PIF |cost=Free |license= |program language= |ref1={{cite journal |author=Siebert X, Navaza J |title=UROX 2.0: an interactive tool for fitting atomic models into electron-microscopy reconstructions |journal=Acta Crystallogr. D Biol. Crystallogr. |volume=65 |issue=Pt 7 |pages=651–8 |year=2009 |month=July |pmid=19564685 |pmc=2703571 |doi=10.1107/S0907444909008671 |url=}} |ref2={{cite journal |author=Navaza J, Lepault J, Rey FA, Alvarez-Rúa C, Borge J |title=On the fitting of model electron densities into EM reconstructions: a reciprocal-space formulation |journal=Acta Crystallogr. D Biol. Crystallogr. |volume=58 |issue=Pt 10 Pt 2 |pages=1820–5 |year=2002 |month=October |pmid=12351826 |doi= |url=}} }}
{{EM software tool |name=V3D |website=http://penglab.janelia.org/proj/v3d |long description=V3D is a general tool for 3D microscopy image visualization and analysis, as well as display and analysis of the extracted surface models. It features fast 3D rendering of large data sets. It comes with a flexible plugin interface which allows developing additional toolkits easily.
V3D is cross-platform and runs on Mac, Linux and Windows. It has a number of easy to use features specially designed for multicolor 3D microscopic data.
|version=2.687 |contact=pengh@janelia.hhmi.org |os support=Mac, Linux, and Windows |image support=tif, LSM, RAW, MRC |cost=Free |license= |program= |ref1={{Cite journal |first1=H. |last1=Peng |coauthors=et al. |year=2010 |title=V3D enables real-time 3D visualization and quantitative analysis of large-scale biological image data sets |journal=Nature Biotechnology |volume=28 |issue=4 |pages=348-353 |pmid= |doi=10.1038/nbt.1612 |pmcid= }} }}
